WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-US

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.760
In filmmaking AI characters&nbsp;
are finally consistent.&nbsp;

00:00:03.760 --> 00:00:05.440
That’s not the problem anymore.&nbsp;

00:00:05.440 --> 00:00:09.920
You don't need multiple tools — or&nbsp;
rebuild your character every time.&nbsp;

00:00:09.920 --> 00:00:15.040
With Google Flow, you create a&nbsp;
character once, I mean face, voice and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:15.040 --> 00:00:19.520
identity... and just reuse it.
Same person in every scene.&nbsp;

00:00:19.520 --> 00:00:26.720
Let’s start by creating a&nbsp;
character that looks real.

00:00:26.720 --> 00:00:28.480
Create a new project.&nbsp;

00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:32.720
You'll have access to both image&nbsp;
and video generation tools.&nbsp;

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:36.480
Now, if you want to create videos&nbsp;
with consistent characters,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:42.400
don't jump straight to video generation.
First, start by creating your characters.&nbsp;

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:48.080
Head over to the Characters section and build&nbsp;
your characters there before moving on to the next step.

00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:51.360
To create a character, you have four options.

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:54.480
First one is using the built-in templates.&nbsp;

00:00:54.480 --> 00:01:01.040
Every time you click a template, it generates&nbsp;
a new prompt and a completely new character.

00:01:01.040 --> 00:01:06.880
The second option is writing your own prompt.
For this, I'm using a Claude skill.

00:01:06.880 --> 00:01:10.320
A skill is basically a system that teaches AI how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:14.240
to build prompts properly.
You create the logic once,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:18.880
then you just give it your inputs.
I simply upload the skill to Claude,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:18.880 --> 00:01:22.880
describe the character I want, and&nbsp;
let it generate the prompt for me.

00:01:22.880 --> 00:01:26.080
Review prompt info and if needed update them.&nbsp;

00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:34.080
Otherwise confirm them.
Copy the prompt and paste it here.

00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:38.400
If you don't like the result, you can&nbsp;
delete it and generate another one.

00:01:38.400 --> 00:01:44.640
The third option is using an image from your&nbsp;
current Flow project—or even another project.&nbsp;

00:01:44.640 --> 00:01:48.720
Then click Add to Character button&nbsp;
to continue creating your character.&nbsp;

00:01:48.720 --> 00:01:51.840
And finally, the option I'm going to use:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:51.840 --> 00:01:55.600
uploading a character image&nbsp;
that I've already created.

00:01:55.600 --> 00:02:00.720
First, give your character a name.
One quick tip: avoid names that are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:06.720
too common or tied to famous people. Sometimes&nbsp;
the model can pull from existing knowledge and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:10.640
that can affect the results.
Next, let's set up the voice.&nbsp;

00:02:10.640 --> 00:02:14.240
You can either pick a voice from&nbsp;
the list or create your own.&nbsp;

00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:19.360
To create a custom voice, start&nbsp;
by selecting a base voice.&nbsp;

00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:30.720
Then give it a name, describe how you want it to&nbsp;
sound, and add a sample line for the AI to read.&nbsp;

00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:33.000
Generate the voice and listen to it.

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:43.760
If you don't like the result, adjust

00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:49.920
the voice description and generate it again.
Once you're happy with it, click Save New Voice.&nbsp;

00:02:49.920 --> 00:02:54.320
Now your custom voice is ready and&nbsp;
you can use it across all your video&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:54.320 --> 00:02:59.600
generations for this character.
Next, we have Character Info.&nbsp;

00:02:59.600 --> 00:03:04.400
This part is optional, but it can help&nbsp;
Flow understand your character better.&nbsp;

00:03:04.400 --> 00:03:08.800
Think about their personality, how&nbsp;
they speak, and how they usually react.&nbsp;

00:03:08.800 --> 00:03:13.280
The more clearly you define your character's&nbsp;
personality, the easier it is to keep&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:13.280 --> 00:03:19.520
them consistent across different scenes.
Next, let's talk about editing your character.&nbsp;

00:03:19.520 --> 00:03:25.000
If you want to make changes, like changing the&nbsp;
hairstyle, or hair color you can do it right here.&nbsp;

00:03:28.080 --> 00:03:34.880
When you click the plus button, Flow automatically&nbsp;
creates a prompt for generating a character sheet.&nbsp;

00:03:34.880 --> 00:03:39.680
This gives the model extra views of your&nbsp;
character, helping it stay more consistent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:39.680 --> 00:03:44.480
across different images and videos.
You can describe the outfit,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:44.480 --> 00:03:51.040
and body here or change all the prompt, then&nbsp;
let Flow generate the character sheet for you.&nbsp;

00:03:51.040 --> 00:03:56.720
Personally, I prefer creating the&nbsp;
character sheet with ChatGPT's image model.&nbsp;

00:03:56.720 --> 00:04:01.680
I simply provide the original character&nbsp;
image and a character sheet template,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:01.680 --> 00:04:05.760
then ask it to generate matching&nbsp;
views of the same character.&nbsp;

00:04:05.760 --> 00:04:11.120
You can make your own template in&nbsp;
Paint, Canva, or any design tool.&nbsp;

00:04:11.120 --> 00:04:17.000
Just update the hairstyle and clothing description&nbsp;
to match your character, and generate the sheet.&nbsp;

00:04:19.920 --> 00:04:25.280
if the result looks good,&nbsp;
download it and upload into Flow.&nbsp;

00:04:25.280 --> 00:04:30.960
Once everything looks right, click Done and your&nbsp;
character will be added to the Characters section.&nbsp;

00:04:30.960 --> 00:04:36.080
From there, you can add it directly to your&nbsp;
prompts or remove it whenever you want.&nbsp;

00:04:36.080 --> 00:04:42.000
And if you ever want to update the voice,&nbsp;
character info, or reference images,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:46.800
just open the character, make your&nbsp;
changes, and click Done again.&nbsp;

00:04:46.800 --> 00:04:52.800
If you want more characters, just&nbsp;
repeat the same steps for each one.

00:04:55.200 --> 00:05:00.960
First, let's see how to use a character in image&nbsp;
generation, and then we'll move on to videos.&nbsp;

00:05:00.960 --> 00:05:04.800
For the first example, I have a&nbsp;
location image and a dog image,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:04.800 --> 00:05:11.760
and I want to place my character in that scene.
This is a very simple image generation workflow.&nbsp;

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:16.960
To use your character, just type @ and&nbsp;
select it from the Characters section.&nbsp;

00:05:16.960 --> 00:05:21.120
You can even import a character&nbsp;
from another project if needed.&nbsp;

00:05:21.120 --> 00:05:26.640
I asked for a full body shot of Rose&nbsp;
walking along this path with her dog.&nbsp;

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:32.800
As you can see, Flow keeps the character&nbsp;
consistent while placing her into the new scene.&nbsp;

00:05:32.800 --> 00:05:36.560
For the next example, I'm&nbsp;
not using any source images.&nbsp;

00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:40.960
Instead, I'm going to generate a&nbsp;
scene using only a simple prompt.&nbsp;

00:05:40.960 --> 00:05:45.200
In this case, I want Rose&nbsp;
climbing a rocky mountain trail.&nbsp;

00:05:45.200 --> 00:05:50.000
If you're not sure how to write a prompt,&nbsp;
just describe your idea in ChatGPT or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:54.800
Claude and let it help you create one.
Then simply mention your character in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:54.800 --> 00:06:00.000
prompt and run the generation.
And here's the final result.&nbsp;

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Same character into a new environment&nbsp;
while keeping her consistent.

00:06:07.760 --> 00:06:12.400
Now let's see how to use the same&nbsp;
character in video generation.&nbsp;

00:06:12.400 --> 00:06:16.400
The first method is generating&nbsp;
a video from an image.&nbsp;

00:06:16.400 --> 00:06:20.800
This is useful when you want to place&nbsp;
your character in a specific environment&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:20.800 --> 00:06:27.440
or combine them with other reference images.
Start by adding your image to the prompt box.&nbsp;

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:31.520
Then write a prompt describing what&nbsp;
you want to happen in the scene.&nbsp;

00:06:31.520 --> 00:06:36.640
After that, mention your character.&nbsp;

00:06:36.640 --> 00:06:41.000
For this example, I'm using&nbsp;Omni Flash
the newest video model.&nbsp;

00:06:41.840 --> 00:06:48.000
Depending on your settings, you can generate&nbsp;
videos between 4 and 10 seconds long.

00:06:59.200 --> 00:07:05.040
Flow gives you two types of references for&nbsp;
video generation: Frames and Ingredients.&nbsp;

00:07:05.040 --> 00:07:10.320
Ingredients help keep characters and&nbsp;
objects consistent across generations.&nbsp;

00:07:10.320 --> 00:07:13.760
However, they don't lock the&nbsp;
first frame of your image.&nbsp;

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:19.440
If you need the video to start from&nbsp;
an exact image, use Frames instead.&nbsp;

00:07:19.440 --> 00:07:23.520
The second method is generating&nbsp;
a video from a text prompt.&nbsp;

00:07:23.520 --> 00:07:30.000
For this example, I'm using a multi-shot prompt.
Mention the character in your prompt to use it.&nbsp;

00:07:45.360 --> 00:07:51.040
As you can see, the model generates&nbsp;
multiple shots based on the prompt.&nbsp;

00:07:51.040 --> 00:07:56.800
You can trim the result or combine it with&nbsp;
additional clips to create a longer video.&nbsp;

00:07:56.800 --> 00:08:02.560
At the moment, Omni Flash doesn't support&nbsp;
extending generated videos directly.&nbsp;

00:08:02.560 --> 00:08:07.280
Instead, I save the last frame of the&nbsp;
video and use it to start a new clip.&nbsp;

00:08:07.280 --> 00:08:10.320
You can save a frame from here.&nbsp;

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:14.960
Then drag it into the prompt area and&nbsp;
write a new prompt for the next scene.&nbsp;

00:08:14.960 --> 00:08:16.515
Don't forget to mention your character again.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:22.000
Generate the new clip and check the result.

00:08:30.800 --> 00:08:36.000
If you're happy with it, go back to the first&nbsp;
video and add the new clip to the timeline.&nbsp;

00:08:56.320 --> 00:09:00.640
You can trim part of the video to&nbsp;
make everything feel more natural.&nbsp;

00:09:00.640 --> 00:09:04.960
When you press Done, Flow saves&nbsp;
all the clips as a single video.&nbsp;

00:09:04.960 --> 00:09:08.160
You can find the final&nbsp;
result in the Scenes section.&nbsp;

00:09:08.160 --> 00:09:14.880
when you click on it, you can continue editing&nbsp;
the video or add more clips whenever you want.&nbsp;

00:09:14.880 --> 00:09:19.520
At the time of recording, all of these&nbsp;
features are available on the free plan.&nbsp;

00:09:19.520 --> 00:09:23.680
Give it a try and let me know what you think.

